## What is next, in the right order

### UX-9A, merge intelligence backend

This is the highest-value next step.

You already created review entry points:

* People quick section,
* merge review action,
* unnamed clusters action.
  And you already have heuristic payloads and lightweight suggestion stubs in the people layer. 

What is missing is a real merge-suggestion engine:

* score candidate cluster pairs using embeddings plus metadata,
* exclude obvious bad pairs,
* rank only the best few suggestions,
* persist accepted / rejected decisions.

This is the biggest value jump because your People UX is now visible, but still heuristic-driven.

### UX-9B, side-by-side person review UI

Once merge candidates are better, make them reviewable:

* left cluster vs right cluster,
* representative faces,
* counts,
* dates / co-occurrence hints,
* Accept merge,
* Reject,
* Not now.

You already have a merge suggestions dialog scaffold concept, so this is the natural next UI layer. 

### UX-9C, unnamed-cluster workflow

After merge review, build a focused workflow for:

* unnamed clusters,
* assign to existing identity,
* mark as distinct new person,
* ignore low-quality cluster.

This matters because your current payload logic already counts unnamed clusters, so the product is asking for that workflow next. 

### UX-9D, facet quality engine

Only after people intelligence improves, tighten facets:

* stronger people facet quality,
* family-aware facet exposure,
* result-set-based counts only,
* fewer noisy facets,
* better browse/search coexistence rules.

This is the right follow-up because facets depend on good metadata and cluster trust.

